{"author": "coding_agent", "parts": [{"text": "Interesting! The WAL file is filled with lots of `0x42` ('B') bytes where we'd normally expect `0x00`. This strongly suggests the WAL file has been XOR'd with `0x42`. Let me verify:\n\nA valid SQLite WAL file should start with the magic number `0x377f0682` or `0x377f0683`. Let me check:"}, {"tool_call": {"name": "run_bash", "args": {"command": "python3 -c \"\n# WAL magic: 377f0682 (little-endian) or 377f0683\n# The first 4 bytes of the WAL are: 75 3d 44 c0\n# XOR with 0x42: 75^42=37, 3d^42=7f, 44^42=06, c0^42=82\nprint(hex(0x75 ^ 0x42), hex(0x3d ^ 0x42), hex(0x44 ^ 0x42), hex(0xc0 ^ 0x42))\n\"\n"}}}]}
{"author": "coding_agent", "parts": [{"tool_response": {"name": "run_bash", "output": "{'result': '[exit 0]\\n0x37 0x7f 0x6 0x82\\n'}"}}]}
{"author": "coding_agent", "parts": [{"text": "The WAL file is XOR'd with `0x42`. `75 3d 44 c0` XOR `42` = `37 7f 06 82` which is exactly the SQLite WAL magic number. Let me decrypt it:"}, {"tool_call": {"name": "run_bash", "args": {"command": "python3 -c \"\nwith open('/app/main.db-wal', 'rb') as f:\n    data = f.read()\n\ndecrypted = bytes(b ^ 0x42 for b in data)\n\nwith open('/app/main.db-wal', 'wb') as f:\n    f.write(decrypted)\n\nprint(f'Decrypted {len(data)} bytes')\nprint(f'First 4 bytes: {decrypted[:4].hex()}')\n\"\n"}}}]}
